<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-325-354  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 325 354.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic News  June 5 1989 v35 n1761 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Major firms claim serious harm if sanctions imposed. (US TradeRepresentative's sanctions against Japanese semiconductorequipment)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Connelly, Joanne.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Major firms in the semiconductor industry are warning that anytrade sanctions levied by the US Trade Representative (USTR)against imported Japanese semiconductor production and testequipment could be harmful to American firms.andP;  The USTR isconsidering levying sanctions against the Japanese in retaliationfor Japan's failure to open its telecommunications markets to USproducts.andP;  Such US firms as IBM and Harris Semiconductor claim agreat dependency on Japanese equipment, saying that certainJapanese hardware - die bonders in particular - are superior toAmerican equipment.andP;  The US firms are urging the USTR to exercisecaution in placing such sanctions as they could result in asignificant risk to the industry.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Semiconductor Production EquipmentSemiconductor industryUnited States. Office of the United States Trade RepresentativeJapanInternational TradeManufacturersUnited StatesTelecommunications.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>